hich she remained on until 30 April when the vessel was moved onto the Rosyth-Zeebrugge route.\n\nIn late May 2012 she was again chartered to [[Seatruck Ferries]] and operated on the Heysham-Warrenpoint route. In April 2014 the repainted ship operates for DFDS between Kiel and [[Kronstadt]].\n\n===Attica Group===\nFollowing a May 2019 agreement between DFDS and [[Attica Group]], the ship was sold to the latter for 12m euros<ref>https://www.attica-group.com/attachments/article/2501/AGREEMENT_FOR_THE_ACQUISITION_OF_A_RO-RO_CARGO_VESSEL.pdf</ref>. As of July 2019, she has been renamed Blue Carrier 1 and bears the greek flag. It is expected to augment the ro-ro freight capacity of Attica Group in its Aegean sea routes.<ref>https://www.naftemporiki.gr/story/1494284/new-ferry-boat-acquired-by-attica-group-renamed-blue-carrier-1</ref>\n\n==Description==\n''Anglia Seaways'' is a roll on-roll off freight ferry 142.5 metres in length capable of carrying 121 trailers or 1,680 [[lane metres]]. It is powered by two Sulzer diesel engines which allow the vessel to reach a speed of {{convert|18|kn|mph}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=M/S MAERSK ANGLIA (2000)|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/maersk_anglia_2000.htm|publisher=Fakta om Fartyg|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|IMO 9186649}}\n* [http://www.dfdsgroup.com/fleet/ro%20ro/angliaseaways/ dfdsgroup.com]\n* [https://archive.is/20130628014616/http://midshipphotos.weebly.com/mv-anglia-seaways.html MV Anglia Seaways photos]\n\n{{Seatruck Ships}}\n\n[[Category:Ships of Seatruck Ferries]]\n[[Category:2000 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in China]]\n[[Category:Merchant ships of Denmark]]\n\n{{Ferry-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAttica Group:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: greek \u2192 Greek", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Carrier_1"}
{"title_page": "Order of Sport", "text_new": "[[File:The_Order_of_Sport_symbol_represents_Canada's_highest_sporting_honour.jpg|thumb|The Order of Sport symbol represents Canada's highest sporting honour]]\nThe '''Order of Sport''' is a National Level Award established in 2019 by [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame|Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame]] and a symbol of the organizations purpose, to build Canada through sport.\n\n== Overview ==\nThe Order of Sport upgrades Canada\u2019s highest sporting honour, induction into Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame, to one connecting sport and social purpose. Commencing 2019, individuals inducted annually into Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame ([[List of members of Canada's Sports Hall of Fame|Hall of Famers]]) receive the Order of Sport in recognition of their continuing role in building [[Canada]] through sport, beyond competition, and the impact they have on their communities.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportshall.ca/order-of-sport.html?lang=EN|title=Canada's Sports Hall of Fame {{!}} Order of Sport|website=www.sportshall.ca|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Canada's Sports Hall of Fame presented the inaugural Order of Sport Award to the class of 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usports.ca/en/news/2019/10/2962846195/canada-s-sports-hall-of-fame-presents-inaugural-order-of-sport-award-to-the-class-of-2019|title=Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame presents inaugural Order of Sport Award to the Class of 2019|website=U SPORTS|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> six athletes and two builders were awarded with the Order of Sport Award.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://calgarysun.com/sports/other-sports/canadas-sport-hall-of-fame-2019-inductees-announced|title=Canada\u2019s Sport Hall of Fame 2019 inductees announced {{!}} Calgary Sun|date=2019-05-23|website=CalgarySUN|language=en-CA|url-status=live|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n[[File:Order_of_Sport_Inaugural_Award_(2019)_-_inscribed_with_recipients_initials_and_date.jpg|thumb|Order of Sport Inaugural Award (2019) - inscribed with recipients initials and date]]\n\n== The Order of Sport Symbol ==\nThe Order of Sport symbol represents the broader and open-ended social purpose of [[Sports in Canada|Sport in Canada]] reflecting the growing cultural significance of sport to Canadians; one that connects Canada\u2019s greatest sports champions to the greater good and was created by [[Design Canada]] film maker and graphic designer Greg Durrell and based upon the Canadian Centennial foundation design work of [[Stuart Ash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/stuart-ash|title=Stuart Ash {{!}} The Canadian Encyclopedia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Order_of_Sport_Award,_Pin,_Pendant_and_Scarf.jpg|thumb|Order of Sport Award, Pin, Pendant and Scarf]]\n\n== Order of Sport Regalia ==\nThe recipients of the Order of Sport Award are presented in the form of an Order of Sport typographic scarf, a Trophy, and Pin or Pendant.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Awards established in 2019]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports trophies and awards]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The_Order_of_Sport_symbol_represents_Canada's_highest_sporting_honour.jpg|thumb|The Order of Sport symbol represents Canada's highest sporting honour]]\nThe '''Order of Sport''' is a National Level Award established in 2019 by [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame|Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame]] and a symbol of the organizations purpose, to build Canada through sport.\n\n== Overview ==\nThe Order of Sport upgrades Canada\u2019s highest sporting honour induction into Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame, to one of sport and social purpose. Commencing 2019, individuals inducted annually into Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame ([[List of members of Canada's Sports Hall of Fame|Hall of Famers]]) receive the Order of Sport in recognition of their continuing role, beyond competition in building [[Canada]] through sport and the impact they have on their communities.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportshall.ca/order-of-sport.html?lang=EN|title=Canada's Sports Hall of Fame {{!}} Order of Sport|website=www.sportshall.ca|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Canada's Sports Hall of Fame presented inaugural Order of Sport Award to the class of 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usports.ca/en/news/2019/10/2962846195/canada-s-sports-hall-of-fame-presents-inaugural-order-of-sport-award-to-the-class-of-2019|title=Canada\u2019s Sports Hall of Fame presents inaugural Order of Sport Award to the Class of 2019|website=U SPORTS|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> six athletes and two builders were awarded with the Order of Sport Award.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://calgarysun.com/sports/other-sports/canadas-sport-hall-of-fame-2019-inductees-announced|title=Canada\u2019s Sport Hall of Fame 2019 inductees announced {{!}} Calgary Sun|date=2019-05-23|website=CalgarySUN|language=en-CA|url-status=live|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n[[File:Order_of_Sport_Inaugural_Award_(2019)_-_inscribed_with_recipients_initials_and_date.jpg|thumb|Order of Sport Inaugural Award (2019) - inscribed with recipients initials and date]]\n\n== The Order of Sport Symbol ==\nThe Order of Sport symbol represents the broader and open-ended social purpose of [[Sports in Canada|Sport in Canada]] reflecting the growing cultural significance of sport to Canadians; one that connects Canada\u2019s greatest sports champions to the greater good and was created by [[Design Canada]] film maker and graphic designer Greg Durrell and based upon the Canadian Centennial foundation design work of [[Stuart Ash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/stuart-ash|title=Stuart Ash {{!}} The Canadian Encyclopedia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Order_of_Sport_Award,_Pin,_Pendant_and_Scarf.jpg|thumb|Order of Sport Award, Pin, Pendant and Scarf]]\n\n== Order of Sport Regalia ==\nThe recipients of the Order of Sport Award are presented in the form of an Order of Sport typographic scarf, a Trophy, and Pin or Pendant.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Awards established in 2019]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports trophies and awards]]\n", "name_user": "Wendyerobertson", "label": "safe", "comment": "some sentence structure and punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_Sport"}
{"title_page": "MS Roald Amundsen", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian hybrid powered cruise ship}}\n{{other ships|Roald Amundsen (ship)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Roald Amundsen''\n|Ship namesake=[[Roald Amundsen]]\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=[[Hurtigruten]]\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Kleven Verft]], [[Ulsteinvik]], [[Norway]]<ref name=\"Cruisemapper\">{{cite web|title=MS Roald Amundsen Review and Specifications\n|url=http://www.cruisemapper.com/ships/MS-Roald-Amundsen-1455|website=CruiseMapper|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down= \n|Ship launched=\n|Ship completed=July 2018<ref name=Cruisemapper />\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification={{IMO|9813072}}\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Active\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage= \n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|140|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"highnorthnews\">{{cite news|last1=Storholm|first1=Linda|title=Two New Expedition Ships to be Named after Polar Heroes|url=http://www.highnorthnews.com/two-new-expedition-ships-to-be-named-after-polar-heroes/|accessdate=13 November 2016|publisher=High North News|date=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n|Ship beam={{convert|23.6|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=highnorthnews />\n|Ship height={{convert|29|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=highnorthnews />\n|Ship draught={{convert|5.3|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"volno\">{{cite news|last1=Bergsli|first1=Gaute|title=Hurtigruten har bestemt seg for navn p\u00e5 sine nye skip|url=http://www.vol.no/nyheter/2016/10/19/Hurtigruten-har-bestemt-seg-for-navn-p%C3%A5-sine-nye-skip-13664175.ece|accessdate=13 November 2016|publisher=Vol.no|date=19 October 2016|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=11<ref name=Hurtigruten />\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed= \n|Ship capacity=530-1018<ref name=volno /><ref name=Hurtigruten />\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''MS ''Roald Amundsen''''' is a new [[Hybrid power|hybrid powered]] [[Hurtigruten]] (Norwegian Coastal Express) expedition cruise ship.<ref name=\"Hurtigruten\">{{cite web|title=MS Roald Amundsen|url=https://www.hurtigruten.com/ships/ms-roald-amundsen/|website=Hurtigruten|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> She has been built by [[Kleven group|Kleven Yards]] of Norway and started her [[maiden voyage]] on  July 3rd 2019 from the Norwegian port [[Troms\u00f8]] to [[Hamburg]].<ref name=Cruisemapper /> She and her sistership {{MS|Fridtjof Nansen||2}} are the first hybrid powered ships in the Hurtigruten fleet.<ref name=highnorthnews /><ref>\nhttps://www.businessinsider.de/das-erste-hybrid-kreuzfahrtschiff-der-welt-geht-in-betrieb-2019-7</ref><ref>https://www.abendblatt.de/hamburg/article226441011/Hybridschiff-mit-530-Passagieren-legt-in-Hamburg-an.html</ref> On the evening of Sept. 10, 2019, the MS Roald Amundsen arrived Nome, Alaska, captained by Kai Albrigtsen, and the operator announced the first complete passage of the more than 3,000 nautical miles passage from the Atlantic to the Pacific, by hybrid propulsion.[https://www.traveldailymedia.com/ms-roald-amundsen-northwest-passage-crossing/]\n\nMS ''Roald Amundsen'' was christened in fall 2019 in Antarctica with a chunk of ice instead of the traditional bottle of champagne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/21233-new-roald-amundsen-set-for-historic-antarctica-christening.html|title=New Roald Amundsen Set for Historic Antarctica Christening|last=Staff|first=C. I. N.|date=2019-07-11|website=www.cruiseindustrynews.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nThe Ship is in the PC6 Polar Class, with a strengthened hull for artic conditions.\n\n== Construction timeline ==\nRoald Amundsen was launched on February 17, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/18541-roald-amundsen-launched-in-norway.html|title=Roald Amundsen Launched in Norway|last=Staff|first=CIN|date=2018-02-17|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2018, Hurtigruten announced that the company wouldn't take delivery of Roald Amundsen until 2019 because of problems at the shipyard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/18583-roald-amundsen-delayed-as-hurtigurten-cancels-inaugural-season.html|title=Roald Amundsen Delayed as Hurtigurten Cancels Inaugural Season|last=Staff|first=CIN|date=2018-02-26|access-date=2018-02-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Itinerary ==\nIn 2019, the ship began expedition cruises along the Norwegian Coast, as well as trips to the North and South Pole. MS ''Roald Amundsen'' was the first hybrid ship to sail the Northwest Passage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/18198-hurtigruten-going-big-in-arctic-in-2019.html|title=Hurtigruten Going Big in Arctic in 2019|last=Staff|first=CIN|date=2017-12-06|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.hurtigruten.com/ships/ms-roald-amundsen/ Hurtigruten ASA Official homepage - MS ''Roald Amundsen'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roald Amundsen, MS}}\n[[Category:Passenger ships of Norway]]\n[[Category:Hurtigruten]]\n[[Category:2018 ships]]\n\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian hybrid powered cruise ship}}\n{{other ships|Roald Amundsen (ship)}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Roald Amundsen''\n|Ship namesake=[[Roald Amundsen]]\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=[[Hurtigruten]]\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Kleven Verft]], [[Ulsteinvik]], [[Norway]]<ref name=\"Cruisemapper\">{{cite web|title=MS Roald Amundsen Review and Specificat