83-roald-amundsen-delayed-as-hurtigurten-cancels-inaugural-season.html|title=Roald Amundsen Delayed as Hurtigurten Cancels Inaugural Season|last=Staff|first=CIN|date=2018-02-26|access-date=2018-02-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Itinerary ==\nIn 2019, the ship began expedition cruises along the Norwegian Coast, aswell as trips to the North and South Pole. MS ''Roald Amundsen'' was the first hybrid ship to sail the Northwest Passage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/18198-hurtigruten-going-big-in-arctic-in-2019.html|title=Hurtigruten Going Big in Arctic in 2019|last=Staff|first=CIN|date=2017-12-06|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.hurtigruten.com/ships/ms-roald-amundsen/ Hurtigruten ASA Official homepage - MS ''Roald Amundsen'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roald Amundsen, MS}}\n[[Category:Passenger ships of Norway]]\n[[Category:Hurtigruten]]\n[[Category:2018 ships]]\n\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eItinerary:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: aswell \u2192 as well", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MS_Roald_Amundsen"}
{"title_page": "MV Oriental Dragon", "text_new": "{{redirect-distinguish|Sun Viking|Viking Sun|Royal Viking Sun}}\n{{About|the ship ordered by the Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=MV ''Oriental Dragon''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\u90f5\u8f2a - panoramio.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Oriental Dragon'' leaving [[Hong Kong]].\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=*''Oriental Dragon'' (2011\u2013present)\n*''Long Jie'' (2007\u20132011)\n*''Omar III'' (2003\u20132007)\n*''Pongnae'' (2001\u20132003)\n*''Hyundai Pongnae'' (1998-2001)\n*''Superstar Sagittarius'' (1998)\n*''Sun Viking'' (1972\u20131998) \n|Ship owner=Capital Dragon Global Holding<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=7125861|shipname=Oriental Dragon|accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref>\n|Ship operator=Island Ship Management, Ltd.<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n|Ship registry=*1972\u20131998: [[Oslo]], {{flag|Norway}}\n*1998\u20132013: [[Panama City]], {{flag|Panama}}\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4|Oy W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 Ab]] [[Hietalahti shipyard|Helsinki Shipyard]], [[Finland]] \n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=394\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship completed=1972\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=*[[Call sign]]: 3FDZ8\n*{{IMO Number|7125861}}\n*{{MMSI|353669000}}\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=In service\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=*{{GRT|18,455}}\n*{{DWT|3,202}}<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|171.69|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"shippingdatabase\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shippingdatabase.com/ship.php?shipid=189512|title=LONG JIE|accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref>\n|Ship beam={{convert|24|m|ft|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"shippingdatabase\" />\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed={{convert|21|kn}}<ref name=\"shippingdatabase\" />\n|Ship capacity=882 (lower berths)<ref name=\"fakta\">{{cite web|last=Asklander|first=Micke|title=M/V VIKING SUN.|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/sun_viking_1972.htm|publisher=Fakta om Fartyg|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n|Ship crew=350<ref name=\"shipparade\" />\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n[[File:Sun Viking Nordkapp 1993.jpg|thumb|left| ''Oriental Dragon'' as MS ''Sun Viking'' in Nordkapp, Norway 1993]]\n[[File:Sun Viking in Vancouver, Canada 1990.jpg|thumb|left|''Oriental Dragon'' as MS ''Sun Viking'']]\n'''MV ''Oriental Dragon''''', originally named ''Sun Viking'', was one of the three original [[cruise ship]]s ordered by [[Royal Caribbean International|Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines]] as part of their early fleet. The ship was first put into service in the year 1972.\n\n[[File:Sun Viking at Ocean Terminal, Hong Kong.jpg|thumb|left|''Oriental Dragon'' as MS ''Sun Viking'']]\nAlong with her sister ships, the [[Song of Norway (ship)|Song of Norway]] and [[Nordic Prince]], the class comprised the first purpose built ships intended for [[Caribbean]] based cruise travel. ''Sun Viking'' cruised the Mexican Riviera on a 7 day itinerary out of L.A. and the Caribbean out of San Juan Porta Rico in the early 1990s. The ''Sun Viking'' was retired in the late 1990s by Royal Caribbean, but remains in service with other cruise lines.<ref>Beneath Crown and Anchor, a History of Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines First 25 Years. [Maxtone Ghram]</ref>\n\n[[File:Omar III (cropped) (recropped).jpg|thumb|left|''Oriental Dragon'' as ''Omar III'']]\nIn 1998 the ''Sun Viking'' was sold to Star Cruises and renamed ''SuperStar Sagittarius''. She was later renamed ''Hyundai Pongnae'' in 2003, sailing for the Hyundai Merchant Marine Company, before being renamed ''Omar III'' for Asia Cruises.<ref name=\"shippingdatabase\" />\n\n[[File:Long Jie on 10 March 2011 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|''Oriental Dragon'' as ''Long Jie'']]\nThe ship was renamed ''Long Jie'' in 2007.<ref name=\"shipparade\">{{cite web|title=Long Jie |url=http://www.shipparade.com/az/Long_Jie/Long_Jie.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201091958/http://www.shipparade.com/az/Long_Jie/Long_Jie.htm |archivedate=2008-12-01 }}</ref> The ''Long Jie'' was put up for sale on June 10, 2010.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} After being dry docked in Singapore, the ''Long Jie'' was transformed into the ''Oriental Dragon'', leaving Singapore on 24 March 2011 bound for Guangzhou, China.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nAfter several years of service as a [[gambling ship]] in Hong Kong, she moved to Penang, Malaysia to continue her career in late 2019.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Media==\nIn the 2018, Oriental Dragon featured in movie [[L Storm]].\n\n==External links==\n* {{csr|register=E|id=7125861|shipname=Oriental Dragon|accessdate=28 April 2012}}\n* [http://www.shipspotting.com/gallery/search.php?search_imo=7125861&page_limit=300 Professional photographs] from shipspotting.com\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|IMO 7125861}}\n<references />\n\n{{Song of Norway class}}\n{{Royal Caribbean Cruise International Ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oriental Dragon}}\n[[Category:Ships built in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:1971 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of Royal Caribbean International]]\n\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-distinguish|Sun Viking|Viking Sun|Royal Viking Sun}}\n{{About|the ship ordered by the Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=MV ''Oriental Dragon''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\u90f5\u8f2a - panoramio.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Oriental Dragon'' leaving [[Hong Kong]].\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=*''Oriental Dragon'' (2011\u2013present)\n*''Long Jie'' (2007\u20132011)\n*''Omar III'' (2003\u20132007)\n*''Pongnae'' (2001\u20132003)\n*''Hyundai Pongnae'' (1998-